England":"Withington, Lancashire, England","Hulme, Lancashire, England":"Hulme, Lancashire, England","Prestbury, Cheshire, England":"Prestbury, Cheshire, England","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Blacon, Chester, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hulme","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Holm   and of   Home   3 and 4."],"variants":[{"name":"Hume","meanings":["Scottish (Lowlands) and northern English: variant of   Hulme  , with loss of <i>l</i> before the bilabial consonant /m/, as in the vocabulary word <i>calm</i>. See   Holm   and   Home  .","Scottish: habitational name either from the barony of Home or from Hume (or Home) in Berwickshire, from which the barony took its name. The placename derives from Old English <i>hōum</i>, dative plural form of <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’.","History: A family of this name (see 2 above) have held the Earldom of Home since 1605."]},{"name":"Holm","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Lars, Anders, Thor, Holger, Nels, Nils, Sven, Helmer, Lennart, Niels, Vibeke.","English, Scottish, German, and Scandinavian: topographic name for someone who lived on an island, in particular a piece of slightly raised land lying in a fen or partly surrounded by streams, from Middle English, Middle Low German <i>holm</i>, Old Norse <i>holmr</i>, or else a habitational name from a place called with this element. The Swedish name is often ornamental.","English: topographic name for someone who lived where holly grew, from Middle English <i>holm</i>, a divergent development of Old English <i>hole(g)n</i> ‘holly (tree)’; or, especially in southern England, a habitational name from any of the places such as East and West Holme (Dorset) or Holne (Devon). Compare   Hollis  ."]}]},{"name":"Bertrand","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval French variant of   Bertram  , imported to Britain by the Normans. In modern times it has been made famous by the English philosopher  Bertrand Russell  (  1872–1970 ), but is only in occasional use."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":84,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Bertrand Hulme was born in 1175, in Withington, Lancashire, England, his father, John Hulme, was 21 and his mother, Mrs John de Hulme, was 17. He had at least 3 daughters. He died in 1275, in Prestbury, Cheshire, England, at the age of 100."},"et":{"1175–1275":"1175–1275","–1303":"–1303","1206–Female":"1206–Surnud","1208–1250":"1208–1250","–Female":"Surnud","1154–1205":"1154–1205","1158–1200":"1158–1200","1275":"1275","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1224":"1224"